WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.920
Welcome, everyone, to the Data Science Hangout. I know a lot of you have been here before,

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:14.640
but if this is your first time, it is an open space for current and aspiring data science

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:20.600
leaders really to just connect and chat about some of the more human-centric questions around

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:25.600
data science leadership. And so we really want to create a space where everybody can

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:32.119
participate and hear from everyone from the community. So there's three ways that you

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.560
could ask questions. You could jump in live, put questions in the chat, and we also have

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:43.400
a Slido link that Rob will share shortly, but you could ask anonymous questions there

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:50.240
too. And just a quick note for everyone that it is recorded, so it will be shared up to

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:57.439
YouTube as well for anybody who's missed it. But I am so excited to introduce my co-hosts

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:05.360
for today's Hangout, Merav, who is co-founder and CEO of Data Society. And Merav, I'd love

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:10.680
to have you also just introduce yourself and share a little bit about the work you do in

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:11.680
Data Society.

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:12.680
Merav Yuravlivker, Data Society, Data Science, rstudio

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:17.480
Thanks, Rachel. Thank you so much for having me. I love doing these types of events, so

00:01:17.559 --> 00:01:22.279
great to see you all. If you have a camera, you feel like turning it on, I love to see people.

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:27.080
If not, that's fine too. I understand people might be running around with kids in the background

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:32.919
and or eating lunch, so that's absolutely acceptable. As Rachel said, my name is Merav

00:01:32.919 --> 00:01:38.120
Yuravlivker, CEO and co-founder of Data Society. Just to give you a bit of a background as to who

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:43.160
I am, I'm a teacher first and foremost. I actually started my career in the classroom way back in the

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:50.120
day in New York City public schools and spent several years in the education space before

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:55.879
starting Data Society. And the reason why we started it is because we saw that there were a

00:01:55.879 --> 00:02:00.040
lot of professionals in the space who needed to understand how to use data, but didn't have

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:06.199
$40,000 to get a master's degree, didn't have hundreds of hours to spend looking through

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:13.559
YouTube videos, and we saw an opportunity to build practical customized training programs

00:02:13.559 --> 00:02:18.919
to deliver specifically to federal agencies as well as Fortune 500 companies to really help

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:25.800
people get up to speed quickly. Because what we believe and I'm sure what a lot of you do as well

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:30.600
is that when you layer a data skill set on top of the industry knowledge that many people already

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:36.679
have, you are really transforming the way that people work and the way that industries run. And

00:02:36.679 --> 00:02:43.160
our goal is to help industries and companies become more data driven because we think that's

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:48.759
what's going to lead to the greatest innovative leaps and it gives us the most power to be able

00:02:48.759 --> 00:02:52.759
to solve a lot of the challenges that we're seeing in today's space. So we're really passionate about

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:57.639
helping people understand how to use data. We also have our consulting side. Frankly,

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:02.360
it just came out of teaching. When you teach what you do, a lot of people ask you to do what you

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:09.240
teach. So we build custom software, predictive algorithms, help with digital transformation,

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:16.039
and we do a lot on that side of it as well. We're based in Washington, D.C., but we have

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:22.360
offices in Richmond and we have folks all over the country, especially as we've gone remote

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:28.600
during the pandemic. So that's a little bit about me and who I am and what I do.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:34.199
Thank you, Merav. And while we're waiting for some questions to come in from the audience,

00:03:34.759 --> 00:03:38.119
I'm just curious, what does that process look like when you start with a new

00:03:38.839 --> 00:03:41.399
client and are starting off that whole training process?

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:48.360
Yeah, that's a good question. We're very much focused on solutions and outcomes. So for us,

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:53.960
every single client that we have has a bit of a consultative approach at first. We talk about what

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:58.440
are the learning objectives, what are people's current skill sets. We also deliver assessments

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:04.199
that can help people actually understand what skill sets are. So we go through that and then

00:04:04.199 --> 00:04:11.320
we develop customized pathways based on those objectives and the starting points. And we have

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:15.639
an in-house team of data scientists as well as instructional designers that work together to

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:20.200
make sure that all the content that we deliver is best of breed. We work with a lot of instructors

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:25.000
who have industry experience. We have in-house instructors as well. And our main goal is really

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.079
to create a good experience where people can walk away and actually immediately start to use the

00:04:31.079 --> 00:04:36.359
skills that they have. So a lot of our programs also have capstone projects, which are a really

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:41.480
great way to demonstrate return on investment and also application of data skills directly

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:45.640
to a challenge that they're facing. There's actually one other piece that I didn't mention,

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:52.519
which is as we expanded our technical training, what we saw is that there's a bigger gap that

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:56.920
we're trying to bridge right now, which is the communication gap between data and non-data

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:01.959
professionals. We've seen that's a really big pain point in a lot of organizations. So we actually

00:05:01.959 --> 00:05:07.079
have our whole non-technical series that works with executives, managers, and general staff,

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:11.079
so that people can all speak the same language because we want to facilitate

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:14.200
that level of collaboration and communication across an organization.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:21.079
That's awesome. I'm thinking that from the audience here, there's also a lot of people who are

00:05:21.079 --> 00:05:25.880
maybe doing this training internally at their organizations or are like the one kind of

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:32.760
spearheading that and getting people interested. So do you have any tips or best practices for

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:40.440
doing that? Yes. First of all, congratulations. That's a really hard job to have. So I'm always

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:45.160
happy to help if you ever want to chat with me specifically about that. One of the biggest ways

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:53.640
that we've seen that can facilitate interest in this type of training is to demonstrate the value

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:59.160
that it has. So if you have data science teams who are using data analytics or there's a particular

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:05.079
project within your industry or your organization that was successful, shout it from the rooftops,

00:06:05.079 --> 00:06:10.040
get some lunch and learns, get that newsletter out. Make sure that people are aware of the benefits

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:14.040
that they can have if they start to implement these skills. And then the other piece of it is

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:19.799
make sure that you have data champions in high places. What we've seen especially to start with

00:06:19.799 --> 00:06:24.519
is if you don't have a mandate from the top to become more data-driven, I mean, most people just

00:06:24.519 --> 00:06:28.279
won't take the time out of their day to learn these skills because they don't feel like it's

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:34.119
mandated. So it has to come from the top. You have to have folks saying, we need to make sure that

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:37.799
we're using these metrics, that you understand what they mean. We need to be asking questions

00:06:37.799 --> 00:06:42.359
about where this data is coming from. We need to make sure that our data is kept securely.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.920
And having that type of conversation come from the top helps give cover to people in a way

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:54.920
who want to take the time out of their day but maybe weren't able to before because

00:06:54.920 --> 00:07:01.079
maybe their direct supervisor didn't see the value in it. So get a data champion that's high

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:07.799
up there and then make sure any successful data projects that you have are well publicized are

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:14.200
two tips that I would give. Thank you and feel free anyone to raise your hand too if you want

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:21.799
to or I can take people unmuting as raising their hand as well. But just to follow up on that, so

00:07:21.799 --> 00:07:24.679
finding that data champion higher up in the company,

00:07:25.799 --> 00:07:30.359
how should you actually go about doing that if you're part of a large organization?

00:07:32.279 --> 00:07:38.200
Yeah, it's not always easy. That's what I'll say. Politics in large organizations can vary.

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:43.399
Sometimes they're less difficult than others. I would say start with the allies you know you have.

00:07:43.399 --> 00:07:48.279
If there's one person, even if they're your colleague as opposed to somebody higher up,

00:07:48.279 --> 00:07:53.239
just get together. Start talking about maybe building something like this, an event like this

00:07:53.239 --> 00:07:58.200
internally, right? Once a month you just meet people who are interested in using data. Start

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:04.040
to get a quorum so that when you go to a supervisor or an executive you can demonstrate the level of

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:11.320
interest that your organization has. The other piece of it is bring in other examples of companies

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:16.600
that might be more data-driven than yours because we all want to make sure we won't become obsolete

00:08:17.399 --> 00:08:24.119
and what I've seen is that organizations now, if they are not going towards this whole

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:30.359
holistic data literacy and building a data culture, if organizations aren't moving towards that,

00:08:31.079 --> 00:08:35.080
it's going to be very difficult for them to keep up with the market in the next five to ten years.

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:38.840
And when you say things like that to an executive audience, they tend to listen.

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:46.039
So if you see that your competitors or other players in your industry are doing this,

00:08:46.039 --> 00:08:49.640
that's another good motivator, especially for those at the executive level.

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:57.640
Thank you. I see a follow-up anonymous question that came in on Slido. When you mentioned

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:02.119
well-publicized, what do you mean by making sure your work's well-publicized?

00:09:03.159 --> 00:09:10.200
So if there is a project that went well, I would look at what avenues you have available to you

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:15.799
to just disseminate that information. I personally love Lunch and Learn because, just like this one,

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:21.799
it highlights a person who's doing a great job and also encourages knowledge sharing across

00:09:21.799 --> 00:09:26.440
an organization. If you have enough people who are participating, it tends to disseminate.

00:09:27.159 --> 00:09:32.440
So I would do that if there are newsletters. I know we work with a very large client who

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:37.080
says they get 20 newsletters a week. Sometimes it's not really the best avenue, but for a lot

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:45.159
of folks, you also might have Slack, you might have Microsoft Teams. If you have any media outlets,

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:49.159
I know that organizations love to show how data-driven they are. So if you are in touch

00:09:49.159 --> 00:09:53.719
with your marketing team or your PR team, throw that at them. That may be something they would

00:09:53.719 --> 00:09:58.840
want to do a little press release about or potentially reach out to one of their contacts.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:04.119
So there are a few different ways to go about it to try to garner that level of attention.

00:10:04.919 --> 00:10:10.840
That's a great point. Frank, I see you asked a question in the chat if you want to ask that live.

00:10:11.799 --> 00:10:12.359
Hi, Frank.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:20.119
Hey, folks. Good to see everyone again. This is a really fascinating way to start the hour.

00:10:20.679 --> 00:10:26.679
You got me wondering, is there any tips that you have to try to find a balance between,

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:31.799
hey, let's do this. We got in a huddle. We have this idea. We have this project. Let's

00:10:31.799 --> 00:10:35.880
see it through. And hopefully, once we get it, we can put it in the newsletter or we can

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.400
put it out there on social media and show people that we're data-driven.

00:10:40.359 --> 00:10:46.359
But man, we can't wait. You don't want to wait 3, 6, 12 months for that cycle to happen.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:53.239
Is there a way that you work faster, I don't know, to experiment to say, oh, yeah,

00:10:53.239 --> 00:10:57.559
this is the right direction. Or no, let's pivot and be OK with pivoting and try something else.

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:06.840
That's a great question. The short answer is it depends on the project you want to focus on.

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:11.559
And it also depends on the data that you have. So especially if you're starting from a point

00:11:11.559 --> 00:11:15.960
where you just want to get something off the ground, start with the data that you have.

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:21.719
Because data collection, I think, as many of us know, can take 3, 6, 9 months depending on the

00:11:21.719 --> 00:11:27.000
type of data that you have. So if you have data that you think can answer maybe one or two

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.159
questions that you have that would be relevant to some of the challenges that your team is facing,

00:11:31.159 --> 00:11:36.440
your department, look for that low-hanging fruit. Because once you have the data,

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:42.200
the cycle to actually go through, cleaning can take a while. Hopefully, your data's in good

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:47.080
shape. But once you have that, it's pretty straightforward to run through any data

00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:51.479
visualizations if you want to build a dashboard. Or alternatively, if you're running it through some

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:57.880
machine learning algorithms, that whole prototyping process is pretty quick.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:02.919
I would also start with a small amount of data just to see if you're on the right track. So

00:12:02.919 --> 00:12:09.880
take a subset of your data, train your model on that, then test it, and then see if it works out.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:14.919
And if not, that's OK. That's all part of the process. It's hard to guarantee a good outcome

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:22.280
when we're doing this type of work. Lovely. Yeah, you got me thinking.

00:12:23.159 --> 00:12:29.960
Thank you. Yeah, I'm a big advocate. It's so hard for especially large organizations. This is not a

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:35.000
one-month project. This is a multi-year project. So I always recommend, especially if you're just

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:39.799
getting started, look for the low-hanging fruit. Where are the people in your company that you know

00:12:39.799 --> 00:12:45.479
would be big advocates for this? Where is the data that you know, if even put into a visual

00:12:45.479 --> 00:12:49.880
interactive dashboard, would garner that type of attention? That's where you want to start with.

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:56.280
I love data visualization because it's usually presented in a way that most people understand,

00:12:56.280 --> 00:13:02.919
and it's less intimidating to executives who might not know how to use data. Everybody loves

00:13:02.919 --> 00:13:07.400
to look at a pretty picture and point to trends, right? That's a nice and easy way to get people

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:15.559
on board. Thank you, Rob. There was an anonymous question earlier that was, how do you measure the

00:13:15.559 --> 00:13:21.400
success of a data science project or client engagement? But also, how do you help companies

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:31.640
define this? So how do we do it as a company? I think that's the question, but probably also how

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:38.359
they could do that as well. Yeah. The key to defining success is defining the metrics that

00:13:38.359 --> 00:13:42.840
you want to look at, and that's true of a data science project. It's true of any of the programs

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:49.400
that we run, because at the end of the day, you could say, is a policy that we've developed

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:53.799
successful, but if you don't know what metrics to measure, it's very hard to answer that question.

00:13:53.799 --> 00:13:57.719
So the first thing that we want to do, that we do, and that I would recommend for anyone

00:13:57.719 --> 00:14:02.840
when starting out with a data science project is, what's the key question you're trying to answer,

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:06.840
and what are the metrics that you're going to use to answer that question? So for example,

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:10.679
if you want to take a look at the effectiveness of a marketing campaign, for example,

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:17.640
the question could be maybe how many people want to buy a certain product or clicked on a

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:22.200
particular ad, and then what are the metrics that you're using? Well, you're probably using people

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:26.599
who click on it, but maybe you also want to take a bit click-through rate. Maybe you'll see that

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:31.159
out of a thousand people that saw it, only five people clicked on the ad. Is that a successful

00:14:31.719 --> 00:14:36.039
rate for you? You would have to compare that against other baseline rates that you've done.

00:14:36.039 --> 00:14:40.840
If you've run another campaign that maybe had a hundred clicks, then maybe that's not a successful

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:45.080
campaign. But if this campaign is garnering clicks and another one didn't, then I would consider that

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:48.520
a success as well. So you want to take the baseline measures, you want to make sure you're

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:52.760
defining your metrics correctly, and you want to also make sure you're answering, asking the right

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:57.559
question. A lot of times, asking the right question and then getting the right data, there's a bit of

00:14:57.559 --> 00:15:02.280
a back and forth there, because if you don't ask the right question at first, you might be collecting

00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:09.400
data and metrics that are not relevant. So what you want to do is just make sure that the metrics

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:14.280
are well-defined before starting any of those projects, and that will help define success.

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:23.880
Thank you. Hugh, I know you asked a question in the chat earlier, and I can see that Libby

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:29.080
gave a plus one to that too. So I'd love to go over to that question next, if you want to ask live.

00:15:30.039 --> 00:15:37.479
Sure. Hey, my name's Hugh. I'm an analyst with the VA. I did want to start with, I love what

00:15:37.479 --> 00:15:42.520
you just said about picking important metrics. My background is like process improvement systems

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:49.559
redesign, and that's a challenge. How do you figure out what customers value and then measure it?

00:15:49.559 --> 00:15:55.239
So I really like that. I like your comment about lunch and learns or forums like this.

00:15:56.039 --> 00:16:02.599
I host a monthly thing internally for VHA, where we do something eerily similar. And one of the

00:16:02.599 --> 00:16:08.840
challenges that I face is, especially since COVID and it's all virtual, sometimes it feels like

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:15.640
you're talking to this nameless, faceless room of people. Do you have any advice on kind of getting

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:24.760
people to participate or chime in so that it's not this more of a monologue than me talking instead

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:29.239
of listening? Thank you. Absolutely. That's a great question. And I'm so glad to hear that

00:16:30.039 --> 00:16:35.880
you're doing that event. I love to hear those types of examples. One way that we found to be

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:41.719
really effective is to break out into small groups. So ask a discussing question and then

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:48.760
break people out into four to five people per group and give the folks five to seven minutes

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:53.559
to discuss the question internally, and then have them come back and designate one person to actually

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:59.159
tell you what they talked about. The reason why I recommend that is because in a large group like

00:16:59.159 --> 00:17:03.719
this, people are generally shy. They know they don't really have to participate, and maybe they

00:17:03.719 --> 00:17:07.400
just want to listen. But when you get folks into a smaller group environment, all of a sudden,

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:13.079
there's more pressure to appear on camera, to participate. So we've seen a lot of people open

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:16.520
up this way. This is how we run a lot of our trainings, actually, now that we're doing

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:20.920
live streaming. And we've even gotten comments from folks saying that it's more interactive than

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:26.040
in-person because they feel like they have to participate. So I would recommend starting off

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:30.680
with an icebreaker like that, even, and then maybe peppering in some of those questions throughout

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:39.160
any presentation that you do. Even if there's less interaction on the big group, I am almost

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:42.760
positive you're going to see more interaction in the small groups, and you're going to see

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:48.199
more development of relationships between colleagues, which I found to be one of the

00:17:48.199 --> 00:17:54.040
most beneficial aspects of any type of event like this. That's awesome. Thank you. My pleasure.

00:17:55.479 --> 00:18:00.199
So the breakouts will start in three, two, one. Yeah, see y'all later.

00:18:00.199 --> 00:18:03.319
That's my way of not talking as much. That's my excuse.

00:18:03.319 --> 00:18:12.280
So, Murav, there's another anonymous question that is, could you give some specific examples

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:21.479
of projects that you've helped clients work through? Absolutely. So I'll give one on the

00:18:21.479 --> 00:18:25.880
consulting side, and then I can give one on the training side as well, just so you see the variety

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:34.040
of work that we do. We recently just finished doing a digital transformation project with a

00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:41.880
financial institution, a small bank that had a lot of disparate data systems and didn't really

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:48.439
understand where to start. They were also really worried about compliance and reporting to federal

00:18:48.439 --> 00:18:54.839
agencies like the FDIC, for example. So we ran a project with them where we did a lot of in-depth

00:18:54.839 --> 00:19:01.239
conversations with their leadership team, took a look at their IT systems, which were, and again,

00:19:01.239 --> 00:19:04.760
this is a nameless company, so I'm not putting them on the spot. There were a lot of Excel

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:11.239
spreadsheets, I'll just say that, which we like to refer to as dark data, which is data that

00:19:11.239 --> 00:19:15.319
remains on one person's laptop and is never, ever, ever shared out to anyone else,

00:19:15.319 --> 00:19:21.880
so this is also just a call-out. If you have a lot of Excel spreadsheets on your laptop,

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:26.119
you know all other colleagues do, try to find a shared drive. Just keep that data somewhere

00:19:26.119 --> 00:19:31.079
