anybody maybe is in a busy room and doesn't want me to call on them to ask their question too,

00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:53.880
you can still put them in the chat, maybe put like a little star at the end

00:26:53.880 --> 00:27:00.520
and I'll know to read it. But Robert asked, how do you gain the trust of a new client

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:04.680
after the engagement starts? In other words, how do you make them feel like your team is

00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:13.160
delivering value? That's a great question. The key to that is communication and clarity.

00:27:13.719 --> 00:27:21.560
What I've found is building trust takes time, of course. And while we say that we have everybody's

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:28.119
best interests at heart, I know that there are folks that have already always had bad experiences

00:27:28.119 --> 00:27:31.400
with people like that, right? So it's not enough to say it, but we have to show it.

00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:37.959
So what does that mean? In terms of our training programs, we usually set up weekly check-ins,

00:27:37.959 --> 00:27:43.880
especially if it's a longer program. We ensure that we solicit feedback from students. So for

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:48.359
some of our longer programs, we also have these very short check-ins. There are typically two

00:27:48.359 --> 00:27:55.239
questions. The first one is how difficult did you find the material? So to help us ensure that we're

00:27:55.959 --> 00:28:01.079
meeting their expectations in terms of skill level. And the second one is how relevant is

00:28:01.079 --> 00:28:06.760
this material to your work to make sure that we're always teaching the most important topics.

00:28:06.760 --> 00:28:11.400
And we also have a section for any additional information. So we keep a pulse on how our

00:28:11.400 --> 00:28:18.280
students are feeling during the class. So if we see anything maybe out of the ordinary, we can

00:28:18.280 --> 00:28:25.000
address it right away. In terms of communication for our consulting projects, we operate very

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:29.719
similarly in terms of that level of communication, ensuring we have those regular touch points,

00:28:29.719 --> 00:28:35.160
ensuring that our clients understand the progress that we're making, and then also making sure that

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:41.719
when issues pop up, we bring them up. I think sometimes clients are afraid to come with me with

00:28:41.719 --> 00:28:47.959
negative feedback. And I get it. Nobody likes to tell somebody anything unpleasant. But for me,

00:28:47.959 --> 00:28:52.359
I welcome it because that's the only way that we grow and that we get better. And if I don't know

00:28:52.359 --> 00:28:58.199
about it, then I won't be able to fix it. So whenever I have conversations like that, the

00:28:58.199 --> 00:29:02.760
first thing I always say is, hey, thank you for bringing this to me. That should be everybody's

00:29:02.760 --> 00:29:07.640
automatic reaction. And then the second piece of it is, let's talk about what we can do, what steps

00:29:07.640 --> 00:29:14.839
we can take to make sure that you are getting what you are expecting from us. So that level of

00:29:14.839 --> 00:29:20.040
communication and clarity tends to mitigate any issues that come about. And then just making sure

00:29:20.040 --> 00:29:25.000
if we see any issues on our side, if the data's not where it's supposed to be, that we bring that

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.880
up right away. So that's a long-winded answer of saying it's just communication more than anything

00:29:29.880 --> 00:29:35.160
else. That's the number one way to build a good relationship. And that's not even in the

00:29:35.160 --> 00:29:41.079
professional field. I would just argue that as a general rule. For sure. And following up on just

00:29:41.079 --> 00:29:45.000
talking a bit more about these projects, someone had asked, what is the best way to deal with

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:50.439
multiple projects? So what is the level of priority that you usually assign to a project

00:29:50.439 --> 00:30:00.520
if this is the case? Yeah. Good question. Well, we're all data people. We love our matrices.

00:30:00.520 --> 00:30:07.800
So I like creating and evaluating against two different axes. The first one is feasibility,

00:30:07.800 --> 00:30:14.119
and the second one is impact. So if there is a project that you've identified is quite feasible

00:30:14.119 --> 00:30:19.719
and has a high level of impact, so that would be in the upper right quadrant for me. You see my

00:30:19.719 --> 00:30:25.560
mirror right here. Then that's the one that I would start with first. And then based on that,

00:30:25.560 --> 00:30:29.239
you can see, OK, maybe there's a project somebody threw in there, but it's actually really difficult

00:30:29.239 --> 00:30:33.319
to get the data, and it's not going to move the needle for us that much. Maybe that would drop to

00:30:33.319 --> 00:30:39.239
a lower priority. So it's really dependent on the objective that your organization has, as well as

00:30:39.239 --> 00:30:45.239
the resources that you have, and then what the timing sense is. Because even for a project that's

00:30:45.239 --> 00:30:51.079
maybe less feasible right now but has a high level of impact, maybe there are some tasks that

00:30:51.079 --> 00:30:56.599
you can start doing now to prepare and to improve the feasibility of that project. So if it's data

00:30:56.599 --> 00:31:00.280
collection, maybe there's something you can run in the background just to start collecting data

00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:04.599
for a project that right now isn't feasible but might be in three months when you have more data.

00:31:07.319 --> 00:31:12.119
Definitely. I see in the chat, Polly, while you were weighing in on this and you have some

00:31:12.119 --> 00:31:20.359
feedback on what you use, feel free to jump in, too. Yeah. When I started my new role, I did a

00:31:20.359 --> 00:31:24.920
couple weeks of meeting with various people and tried to find a way to rank projects. And we

00:31:24.920 --> 00:31:30.199
landed on this, what you're saying. One, how hard is it? Two, what's the impact? And then three,

00:31:30.760 --> 00:31:36.199
is the business ready for this or not? Which is related to impact but not quite. So we developed

00:31:36.199 --> 00:31:42.839
an internal weighted number and then scaled it from zero to 100 to figure out what to do first.

00:31:44.119 --> 00:31:48.839
Using data just to determine those projects. I love it. That's great. I like business readiness

00:31:48.839 --> 00:31:53.479
a lot. I think that's important. We get a lot of clients who ask us to do neural networks off the

00:31:53.479 --> 00:31:58.760
bat. And I'm like, well, let's talk about the data that you have and then we'll see how it goes from

00:31:58.760 --> 00:32:07.719
there. Executives like to throw around terms that they're seeing without necessarily understanding

00:32:07.719 --> 00:32:12.199
the implications behind it. So it's one of the, again, this goes back to building trust. One of

00:32:12.199 --> 00:32:18.520
the biggest pieces and biggest responsibilities that we have is to educate whoever we're speaking

00:32:18.520 --> 00:32:22.280
with to make sure they understand what they're actually asking for. Because a lot of time what

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:27.079
clients are asking us to do versus what they actually need can be different. So that's why

00:32:27.079 --> 00:32:30.680
we like to dig in there to make sure that we're addressing what the actual need is.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:39.719
I see there's a quite a few other anonymous questions that were asked earlier. And one was,

00:32:39.719 --> 00:32:44.520
how do you go about from building to serving a predictive model for your projects?

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:56.599
Yep. So in terms of building the model, we have a framework that we use. We also teach.

00:32:56.599 --> 00:33:01.400
And it has six steps. I'm sure that there are variations of this all over the place, but we

00:33:01.400 --> 00:33:06.520
always start with asking the question. So like I mentioned earlier, without the right question,

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:12.199
it is very difficult to build a model that will make an impact. So you want to ask the right

00:33:12.199 --> 00:33:17.800
question. You want to make sure that you have the right data. Honestly, that will take 70 to 80%

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:24.359
of any data project time because collecting data and cleaning data can be very labor intensive.

00:33:24.359 --> 00:33:28.599
And that also goes back to the piece of setting up the appropriate data infrastructure and having

00:33:28.599 --> 00:33:33.400
the right data governance in place. Because if you do have both of those pieces, it dramatically

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:39.319
shortens the amount of time that your data scientists need to spend in R or Python just

00:33:39.319 --> 00:33:44.359
wrangling the data and manually understanding it. Once you have that, depending on what the

00:33:44.359 --> 00:33:48.760
objective is, you'll determine which algorithm makes the most sense. So if you're just starting

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:54.040
out with unlabeled data and trying to understand different types of groups that your data falls

00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:57.400
into, you might want to do something like clustering, which is a well-known unsupervised

00:33:57.400 --> 00:34:02.359
machine learning algorithm. If you already have data that has existed and you're trying to predict

00:34:02.359 --> 00:34:08.120
trends or categories, you might do something like classification, maybe with a random forest or

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:15.320
something like that. And use a part of your training data for that to build a model.

00:34:15.320 --> 00:34:19.159
And of course, you always want to test it. And then you want to validate it with real world data.

00:34:19.159 --> 00:34:24.840
And then the last piece of it is interpreting the results. So you might take a look at the data

00:34:24.840 --> 00:34:29.080
and you might say, OK, based on the set of recommendations that this algorithm is

00:34:29.080 --> 00:34:34.520
giving me, I want to create three different targeted marketing campaigns going on at

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:38.360
different time frames. Or if I'm a financial institution, maybe I want to understand who

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:44.520
is the best type of person to loan to and to underwrite. And then how do I identify those

00:34:44.520 --> 00:34:51.399
people? So a lot of times that's the typical framework. And there's a lot of back and forth,

00:34:51.399 --> 00:34:56.280
so it sounds linear right now. But during the actual process, you should be prepared to

00:34:56.280 --> 00:35:01.479
go back and try different algorithms. A lot of times people like to build several different

00:35:01.479 --> 00:35:06.919
models to determine which one presents the most accuracy. You'll also want to take into account

00:35:06.919 --> 00:35:12.120
what does accuracy mean to you. So just to give you an example, if you're building an algorithm

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:17.239
for the Air Force to determine how often planes need to come in for maintenance, you really want

00:35:17.239 --> 00:35:21.399
to err on the side of caution for that. If you wait too long and planes start falling out of

00:35:21.399 --> 00:35:26.840
the sky, it's going to be a really big problem. So your accuracy level, you might need to adjust

00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:32.439
your parameters to be as conservative as possible. So a lot of that also depends on inputs that you

00:35:32.439 --> 00:35:37.719
can give your data science team to make sure that you're prioritizing the appropriate business cases.

