00:59:59.080 --> 01:00:03.239
It's been a while since we built them. Sometimes we use an iframe, and we post it also internally

01:00:03.239 --> 01:00:09.080
on our website depending on what the tool is. We actually built a Shiny apps dashboard. I don't

01:00:09.080 --> 01:00:15.159
know if it's still running. For the White House about five years ago, we participated in the

01:00:15.159 --> 01:00:20.600
Opportunity Project, which I'm not sure if you're all aware of, but it's a great initiative that

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:27.239
pairs industry folks with agency people to solve a particular challenge. At that time, we worked

01:00:27.239 --> 01:00:32.600
with the Department of Education. We built out a dashboard that mapped school resources

01:00:32.600 --> 01:00:37.879
in the city of Philadelphia to help people understand both what resources were close to

01:00:37.879 --> 01:00:43.879
schools. They could also compare different schools within a county and help determine

01:00:43.879 --> 01:00:49.320
if there's no library within a mile of a school. Is that a place to put a library or a grocery

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:54.280
store? Because food deserts are also a really big issue. Shiny dashboards are great. I think we

01:00:54.280 --> 01:01:00.520
hosted it on shinyapps.io, if I remember correctly. That's great. Do they run that every year?

01:01:01.159 --> 01:01:07.399
They do. They do run it every year. I'll have to check out that link. I just want to

01:01:07.479 --> 01:01:11.560
double check with everyone. Are there certain questions that I maybe have missed? I'm trying

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:19.399
to do my best to scroll through, but feel free to speak up live too. I've got a very short one.

01:01:21.479 --> 01:01:26.679
We talked a lot about explaining algorithms to business users and business users having

01:01:26.679 --> 01:01:33.879
an aversion to using that output and learning more about that. It made me think it's very easy

01:01:34.120 --> 01:01:38.679
for me to say, oh yeah, come on. It's just multivariate regression. You shouldn't be

01:01:38.679 --> 01:01:43.239
scared of it. I'm trying to think on the flip side of that, are there people or groups that

01:01:43.239 --> 01:01:50.199
come to me and say, hey, this is the direction we should go. You should be on board. I'm like,

01:01:50.840 --> 01:01:54.679
I don't feel great about that. I do first person there, but I'm curious,

01:01:55.800 --> 01:02:01.159
is there anything that comes to your mind from that perspective that you are averse to?

01:02:04.040 --> 01:02:07.399
That's a good question. Also, a lot of good questions today.

01:02:10.280 --> 01:02:14.360
So far, we haven't been asked to do anything that I think is ethically questionable. I'll

01:02:14.360 --> 01:02:17.879
just put it that way, although I know that that happens a lot. Of course, there's a lot

01:02:17.879 --> 01:02:21.479
of discussion now with everything that's happening on Facebook. What I will say is,

01:02:21.479 --> 01:02:26.360
I'll just add on to what you were saying, which is I did put a lot of responsibility on business

01:02:26.360 --> 01:02:30.840
people. What I didn't mention is that sometimes it's really difficult for data scientists to

01:02:30.840 --> 01:02:35.800
communicate just effectively in general. So the flip side to that is making sure that your data

01:02:35.800 --> 01:02:40.760
scientists can understand the business enough to be able to connect with other business users.

01:02:42.199 --> 01:02:46.280
There is actually, shoot, I can't remember the name of it. There was a book that was recommended

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:56.199
to me recently that was about communication for technical people to speak business,

01:02:57.159 --> 01:03:01.320
and I'm blanking on the name right now, but it has a big yellow cover on it. I'll see if I can

01:03:01.320 --> 01:03:06.520
find it. So what I would recommend is on the flip side as well, just making sure that your data

01:03:06.520 --> 01:03:11.159
scientists feel comfortable speaking to some business use cases will also help facilitate

01:03:11.159 --> 01:03:15.239
that. I think it is a two-way street, although we usually find one more than the other.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:17.479
Thank you.

01:03:18.199 --> 01:03:18.760
My pleasure.

01:03:19.399 --> 01:03:22.919
Thank you so much, Rob. Can I ask you one last question?

01:03:22.919 --> 01:03:23.399
Absolutely.

01:03:23.719 --> 01:03:29.560
So for people on the call who are hoping to get into a data science leadership role

01:03:29.560 --> 01:03:34.600
or maybe start their own company like you, what advice would you give them?

01:03:37.239 --> 01:03:40.679
If you're going to start a company, make sure you're financially stable

01:03:41.399 --> 01:03:44.840
and just let your friends and family know you won't see them for a few years.

01:03:45.479 --> 01:03:51.239
That's my first piece. It is very time consuming. It's incredibly rewarding. It takes a lot of time.

01:03:51.879 --> 01:03:56.199
You have to really love solving challenges and figuring ways out in situations,

01:03:56.199 --> 01:04:01.479
especially if you're bootstrapped like we are. Obviously, if you are funded by investors,

01:04:01.479 --> 01:04:06.040
there's a different set of challenges there. If you're looking to become more in that data

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:10.919
leadership role, I would say communication, just as we've talked about before, is incredibly

01:04:10.919 --> 01:04:18.439
important. So make sure that you feel comfortable communicating the importance of data and that

01:04:18.439 --> 01:04:22.520
you can also demonstrate that as well. So in your presentation, start to bring in

01:04:22.520 --> 01:04:26.919
data-driven results and research and really define yourself as the data person.

01:04:28.600 --> 01:04:34.280
Just put yourself in that role because that's what we've seen happen a lot with people who are

01:04:34.280 --> 01:04:38.520
self-made data scientists and things like that. They just want to solve a challenge. They get

01:04:38.520 --> 01:04:43.239
more involved in it, and that's how they grow their skills. So I would recommend if you want

01:04:43.239 --> 01:04:48.840
to spearhead those types in Lunch and Learn, do it. There's not a ton that's stopping us from

01:04:48.840 --> 01:04:55.879
creating these types of informal sessions. Just keep at it. It's a lot of work. It's a lot of

01:04:55.879 --> 01:05:01.879
work, but the end is really rewarding when you get to see challenges like helping people identify

01:05:01.879 --> 01:05:08.280
where the opioid crisis is most critical or where some of those prescriptions are coming from so

01:05:08.280 --> 01:05:13.879
that we can help nip it in the bud. Helping predict outbreaks of COVID in nursing homes,

01:05:13.879 --> 01:05:20.600
right? All of these critical things that are impacting our day-to-day lives. Getting goosebumps

01:05:20.600 --> 01:05:25.399
talking about it now because this is really rewarding to see that type of an impact that

01:05:25.399 --> 01:05:32.280
we can have and that all of you can have too. Thank you so much, Miranda. I really appreciate

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:37.800
you jumping on and chatting with all of us. That was awesome. Really appreciate your insights too.

01:05:38.679 --> 01:05:42.360
My pleasure. Really good questions. I appreciate everybody being so interactive.

01:05:43.239 --> 01:05:49.239
It makes my life a lot easier and more fun too to do this type of thing, so I'm really glad you all

01:05:49.239 --> 01:05:52.600
were able to come today. Feel free to connect with me on LinkedIn. I'm sure there's only one

01:05:52.600 --> 01:05:57.959
Morav here on there. You can find me pretty easily, or feel free to send me any additional

01:05:57.959 --> 01:06:02.520
notes, emails. If you want to chat about anything, just morav.datasociety.com,

01:06:02.520 --> 01:06:07.000
and really best of luck on your data journeys. I hope this was helpful and informative to you.

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:13.479
Thank you all for joining as well. Have a great rest of the day. We'll put the recording up on

01:06:13.479 --> 01:06:19.320
YouTube too, so I can put the link to Data Society there as well. Thank you so much,

01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:21.080
Miranda. Have a great rest of the day.

